SIMPLE: murmur
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Murmur
<hw>Mur"mur</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>murmure</ets>: cf. L. <ets>murmur</ets>. CF. <er>Murmur</er>,
<pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A low, confused, and indistinct
sound, like that of running water.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A complaint half suppressed, or uttered in a low,
muttering voice.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some discontents there are, some idle <qex>murmurs</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murmur</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Murmur
<hw>Mur"mur</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Murmured</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Murmuring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>murmurer</ets>, L.
<ets>murmurare</ets>, <ets>murmurari</ets>, fr. <ets>murmur</ets>
murmur; cf. Gr. <?/ to roar and boil, said of water, Skr.
<ets>marmara</ets> a rustling sound; prob. of imitative origin.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To make a low continued noise, like the hum of bees, a
stream of water, distant waves, or the wind in a forest.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>murmured</qex> as doth a swarm of bees.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To utter complaints in a low, half-articulated
voice; to feel or express dissatisfaction or discontent; to grumble; --
often with <xex>at</xex> or <xex>against</xex>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧His
disciples <xex>murmured</xex> at it.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>John vi.
61.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And all the children of Israel <qex>murmured</qex> against Moses
and against Aaron.</q> <rj><qau>Num. xiv. 2.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Neither <qex>murmur</qex> ye, as some of them also
<qex>murmured</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>1 Cor. x. 10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murmur</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Murmur
<hw>Mur"mur</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To utter or give forth in low or
indistinct words or sounds; <as>as, to <ex>murmur</ex> tales</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The people <qex>murmured</qex> such things concerning him.</q>
<rj><qau>John vii. 32.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murmuration</ent>⟦br⟧
